  IT is heartening to see the country’s main political leaders calling for subordination of political differences and forge unity in the fight against the Covid-19 pandemic.
The disease has since the beginning of this year mercilessly ravaged the country. Over 1 000 people have perished out of more than 30 000 infections logged since the coronavirus pandemic hit our shores in march 2020. More than 600 deaths were recorded in January this year alone. The devastating effect of the pandemic has jogged President Emmerson Mnangagwa, MDC leader Douglas Mwonzora and his MDC Alliance counterpart Nelson Chamisa to rally for unity in confronting the monster. This followed the recent death of three government ministers, Foreign Affairs minister Sibusiso Busi Moyo, Transport minister Joel Biggie Matiza and Manicaland Provincial Affairs minister Ellen Gwaradzimba from the lethal virus. Mnangagwa last weekend called for unity among Zimbabweans in the fight against Covid-19, which he said was a pestilence that has affected most families in the country regardless of political affiliation. Mnangagwa said unity had brought about victory for Zimbabweans previously during the war of liberation that culminated in independence in 1980. The following day, Chamisa buttressed the call. “It is time we work together to stop the spread of Covid-19. Unity is key in the face of this pandemic. All of us must put aside our political jackets, remove our political robes, political differences and work together in this fight,” Chamisa said. The call of unity in the fight against the coronavirus pandemic should cascade into a national dialogue to resolve the country’s myriad of political and economic challenges. The people’s hope is that soon the political gladiators will not only put their heads together on how to tackle the Covid-19 pandemic, but the political and economic crises. Long-suffering Zimbabweans have been demanding national dialogue and this is the opportune time for our main  political leaders to pave the path for it. It is humbling that Chamisa spoke passionately about coming up with local solutions to resolve internal problems. It’s time for Mnangagwa, Mwonzora and Chamisa to utilise their calls for unity in fighting coronavirus to kick start the long-awaited national dialogue. We are optimistic talks are nigh! Sponsored Links

    
      
        
          
